Einstein formulated the theory of special relativity, largely to describe the effects of high speed on the motion of matter.
He described space as being absolute with time being relative to objects moving relative to each other. He observed that the time dilation for objects moving relative to each other is exactly the same as the time dilation for any observer's perception as relative to the speed of light. The formula for doing this was given by
\(d \tau = \frac{\Delta t}{\sqrt{1- \left(\frac{v}{c}\right)^2}} \)
where \(d \tau\) was the time differential for the frames due to velocity, and \(\Delta t\) was the familiar time differential for the object.
